Here is an example of automatically generating a table of contents in LaTeX:

\documentclass{report}

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\chapter{Introduction}

\section{Motivation}

\section{Overview} 

\chapter{Background}

\section{Related Work}

\section{Problem Definition}

\chapter{Proposed Method} 

\section{Approach}

\section{Implementation}

\end{document}

The \tableofcontents command generates the table of contents by reading the sectioning commands like \chapter, \section, etc. used in the document. LaTeX automatically updates the TOC whenever these sectioning commands are added or modified in the document.

Here is the LATEX code to draw a chessboard from a FEN notation string:

\documentclass{article}

\usepackage{chessboard}

\begin{document}

\fenboard{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1}

\end{document}

The key points:

- The chessboard package is required to draw chessboard diagrams.
- \fenboard takes the FEN string as its argument and draws the board.
- The FEN string fully specifies the position of all pieces on the board.

This code would take any valid FEN string and render the corresponding chess position as a diagram. The chessboard package handles all the details of parsing the FEN and drawing the pieces in the correct squares.

